How does the stock market absorb shocks
Authors: Frank, Sanati
Year: 2018
Data Used: S&P500, FT (From 1984 to 2013)
Methodology:
1. Identify shocks using standardised data
2. Determine if the shock contains news by matching to news database
3. Calc cumulative abnormal return (relative to the market return)
Key Findings:
If positive news: Likely to reverse. Mainly contributed by retail investors
If negative news: Likely to persist
If no news: Likely to reverse
Economic Intuition:
If a fund wants to sell off after bad news, it has to do so gradually
If the shock origination is non-fundamental, liquidity providers quickly step in, hence reversal